band\", describing him as a \"peaceful, selfless man\".</p><p>Henning, a former taxi driver from Manchester, was taken hostage last December in Syria by Islamic State (Isis) militants.</p><p>The 47-year-old aid worker was <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/13/isis-video-david-haines-beheading\" title=\"\">shown at the end of a video</a> last week after the beheading of fellow British captive David Haines.</p><p>Henning's wife Barbara said she has sent messages to Isis asking them to release her husband but has had no response.</p><p>In a statement released through the Foreign Office she said: \"Alan is a peaceful, selfless man who left his family and his job as a taxi driver in the UK to drive in a convoy all the way to Syria <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/17/alan-henning-syria-friend-appel-aleppo-al-baghdadi\" title=\"\">with his Muslim colleagues and friends</a> to help those most in need.</p><p>\"When he was taken he was driving an ambulance full of food and water to be handed out to anyone in need.</p><p>\"His purpose for being there was no more and no less. This was an act of sheer compassion.</p><p>\"I cannot see how it could assist any state's cause to allow the world to see a man like Alan dying.\"</p><p>It is the first time Henning's family has issued a public statement since he was threatened in the Isis video earlier this month.</p><p>The extremist group has previously released footage showing the killing of American journalists James Foley and Steven Sotloff.</p><p>A separate <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/18/islamic-state-video-isis-uk-hostage-propaganda-message-gunpoint\" title=\"\">video released this week showed British photojournalist John Cantlie</a> sitting at a desk reading from a prepared script and explaining that he would speak about Isis in future videos. There was no threat to kill Cantlie made on camera.</p><p>A series of pleas for the release of Henning have been made by high-profile Muslim leaders in recent days, warning Isis that the killings and threats are against Sharia law.</p><p>Renowned Jihadi ideologue Muhammed al-Maqdisi and the family of jailed Pakistani scientist Dr Aafia Siddiqui, nicknamed \"Lady al Qaida\", whose release has been demanded by Isis extremists, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/19/isis-muslim-scholars-call-release-alan-henning-hostage\" title=\"\">have also called for Henning to be released</a>.</p>","headline":"Alan Henning's wife calls on Islamic State militants to release her husband","trailText":"<p>British aid worker, 47, taken hostage in Syria in December after travelling to the country to distribute food and water</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"2","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/9/21/1411254459240/Iraq-conflict-006.jpg","wordcount":"344","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"447723673","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"9550162","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Caroline Davies","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-09-22T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2161886","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-09-23T23:08:17Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/sep/21/alan-henning-wife-calls-isis-to-release-him-syria","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/uk-news/2014/sep/21/alan-henning-wife-calls-isis-to-release-him-syria","tags":[{"id":"uk/uk","webTitle":"UK news","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/uk","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/uk/uk","references":[]},{"id":"world/isis","webTitle":"Islamic State (Isis)","description":"The latest news and comment on the Islamic State (Isis) militant group","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/isis","apiUrl":"http://content.guar